INSERT INTO `opus_posts` VALUES (7,1,'2017-07-07 05:17:51','2017-07-07 09:17:51','','logo-opus','','inherit','closed','closed','','logo-opus','','','2017-07-07 05:17:51','2017-07-07 09:17:51','',0,'http://opusinside.hotsauceatl.com/wp-content/uploads/logo-opus.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(8,1,'2017-07-07 05:25:17','2017-07-07 09:25:17','','logo-opus-16','','inherit','closed','closed','','logo-opus-16','','','2017-07-07 05:25:17','2017-07-07 09:25:17','',0,'http://opusinside.hotsauceatl.com/wp-content/uploads/logo-opus-16.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(9,2,'2017-06-20 12:00:15','2017-06-20 16:00:15','<strong>Chief Technology Officer Mike Angle works directly with CISOs and IT risk professionals across global banks and corporations on the complex challenges of information security risk, particularly as they pertain to managing third parties.</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>It’s not just an academic exercise for Mike: he’s also in charge of information security for Opus. As a global SaaS company serving enterprises with sensitive information, staying vigilant against cyber risk is way of life for Mike. We sat down and spoke with him on why third party information security — or “infosec,” for short — </strong><strong>is such a burning issue today, and why he recommends a controls-based approach to manage it.</strong>\r\n\r\n<!--more--><strong>Q: What does information security risk mean to you?</strong>\r\n\r\nInformation security risk means understanding the vulnerabilities you have as a firm for dealing with how your information is potentially exposed, whether on the internet or through other channels.\r\n\r\nIt’s pretty simple. Bad actors can come in and do bad things to your data. They can steal your data. They can corrupt your data. They can hold your data for ransom. You need to protect it.\r\n\r\n<strong>Q.: How has the information security situation changed over the past few years? Why is it so challenging out there for CISOs?</strong>\r\n\r\nYears ago, information and data were pretty easy to control. In the days of mainframes, or “big iron,” you knew where all your data was. You knew who had access to the data. It was relatively straightforward to manage.\r\n\r\nToday, information security is truly a burning issue. Probably the biggest challenge a CISO faces is just understanding all the different vectors their data is vulnerable through.\r\n\r\nNot only are your employees bringing in their own devices and creating all sorts of security holes themselves, but there’s a myriad of third parties you’re connected to, many of whom are hard to track down.\r\n\r\n<strong>Q: Is regulation an issue?</strong>\r\n\r\nAbsolutely — there are increased regulatory mandates on information security, particularly in financial institutions. But well beyond regulatory compliance, you really need to make sure bad things don’t happen to your firm. Criminal organizations are becoming more sophisticated in their technologies and threats can come from anywhere. If you are systemically important in a handful of industries such as banking, you need to consider the possibility you will be targeted by state actors as well.\r\n\r\n<strong>Q: You mentioned third parties. What are third parties and why are they of such concern?</strong>\r\n\r\nWell, we all know about the Target breach a few years ago. The initial intrusion was traced back to network credentials stolen from a third-party HVAC contractor. That’s one of the best-known examples.\r\n\r\nTraditionally, many of us have dealt with managing vendors and those are relatively easy to understand. You have typical traditional vendor contracts where they specify SLAs, etc.\r\n\r\nBut the world is increasingly filled with non-traditional vendors, suppliers and other partners. In fact, the OCC actually calls out non-traditional vendors as a key area for financial institutions to focus on in their third-party management programs.\r\n\r\nOne good example is law firms. Companies often send law firms highly proprietary or highly personalized information about clients. You wouldn’t typically think of them as being a vendor or a third party with risk of an information security breach. But they can be.\r\n\r\nThird parties are often highly trusted and are granted full access to systems and data.\r\n\r\n<strong>Q: So why is managing these third parties so hard?</strong>\r\n\r\nThe challenges I hear from CISOs today are largely around the cost and complexities of implementing a third-party vendor management program. It requires a huge number of questions be asked of the vendor or third parties. It requires relatively experienced examiners to go in and do on-site assessments to make sure the vendor both understood the question, answered in a way that is normalized to what you expect, as well as whether the programs the third party has in place are actually effective in meeting the needs for information security.\r\n\r\n<strong>Q: How has Opus addressed this need?</strong>\r\n\r\nWell, we’ve talked to a number of CISOs who have been struggling with just the huge amount of information that needs to be consumed in order to do a third-party risk assessment.\r\n\r\nThe typical state of the art is a questionnaire like the SIG (Standardized Information Gathering Questionnaire), on the order of 1500 questions. Just the data management challenge of going through that, organizing that is tough.\r\n\r\nAnd then how do you evaluate that? How do you evaluate a vendor against 1500 questions? Is 1400 enough? Is 900 enough?  And who does all the work?\r\n\r\nWe have taken a controls-based approach to information security. A controls-based approach means you are basically focused on the <strong>goals</strong> of an information security assessment and not just individual questions.\r\n\r\nSo no longer are you looking at simple litmus tests, yes and no answers to individual questions, but you’re actually evaluating those questions and the evidence your vendor has provided you against a set of industry-accepted goals for information security across broad areas, such as access control, malware defense, etc.\r\n\r\nAnd that’s really important in a world where there’s sometimes more than one way to get to a goal. For example, access to your systems. In some firms, I log in with a user ID and a password. In some firms, I have two-factor authentication. The password’s dynamically created and challenged. Not every situation is the same so a black and white approach falls short.\r\n\r\n<strong>Q: Why do you recommend a controls-based approach?</strong>\r\n\r\nControls focus on goals instead of individual questions. And in our solutions, for the first time, we can stop putting the answers in spreadsheets. We don’t have to fight with technology that doesn’t work. It allows us to proceduralize how we do these assessments, and really critically, because answers are now stored in a database, we can start to mine that information. We can for the first time, really understand where our third party risks are, where we need to focus our remediation efforts, and where we can feel comfortable.\r\n\r\n<strong>Q: Any final words of advice?</strong>\r\n\r\nThe most important thing is to understand how managing third parties differs from what you’re already doing on the inside of your organization. Granted, in some ways, you’re looking for the same sorts of things. Are they following best practices? Do they have virus detection on all their machines? Do they rotate their passwords?\r\n\r\nBut what makes it different is that with third parties, the communication becomes so important. You have lots of questions to ask them, lots of answers to get back. There’s a huge multiplier. Firms I talk to have hundreds to thousands of third parties, and the communication becomes a big challenge as well because you need to manage the flow of information out to your vendors and suppliers, getting responses back, collecting documents, asking follow-on questions, etc.\r\n\r\nIf you try to do this in spreadsheets, or through emails, or some other technology that’s not really suited to purpose, you just consume a huge amount of your info sec professional’s time. Time equals money. It’s just not an effective approach.\r\n\r\n<strong>Questions for Mike? Reach him at michael.angle@opus.com</strong>\r\n\r\n<strong>Want to know more about information security? Download the <a href=\"http://opusglobal.uptrending.com/resource/hiperos-3pm-information-security/\">solution fact sheet</a></strong>','“Information Security Risk is Truly a Burning Issue”','','publish','closed','closed','','information-security-burning-issue-interview-opus-cto-mike-angle','','','2017-07-10 15:26:53','2017-07-10 19:26:53','',0,'http://opusinside.hotsauceatl.com/?p=9',0,'post','',0),(11,1,'2017-07-07 07:11:40','2017-07-07 11:11:40','','post-img1','','inherit','closed','closed','','post-img1','','','2017-07-07 07:11:40','2017-07-07 11:11:40','',9,'http://opusinside.hotsauceatl.com/wp-content/uploads/post-img1.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(15,3,'2017-05-02 12:00:53','2017-05-02 16:00:53','Your organization is increasingly dependent on third parties to grow revenue, manage costs and capture market opportunities.  Your suppliers, vendors, contractors, distributors, agents, brokers, channels, joint ventures, partners and other third parties are critical to the growth and profitability of your company.\r\n\r\nYour company has policies for training employees – when they first join the company and on an ongoing basis. Do you have policies for training your third parties?  If so, how are they implemented and managed?\r\n\r\nFor most organizations, delivering and managing training for third parties has become one of the most challenging aspects of developing and enforcing specific corporate risk, compliance and performance initiatives.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->Recent surveys from analysts, as well as our own research indicates that training of third parties is a challenge that the majority of companies have yet to address:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><strong>16%</strong> of companies require training of all of their third parties</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>22%</strong> do so for some third parties</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>62%</strong> do no third party training</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nDo you belong to one of these category?\r\n<strong>New blueprint: 5 Steps for Delivering and Managing third Party Training Programs</strong>\r\n\r\nBlueprint for Third Party Training is an introductory guide to developing training programs for third parties that are cost-effective, highly scalable and auditable.\r\n\r\n<strong><a href=\"http://promotions.hiperos.com/opus-training-blueprint\">Read blueprint here</a></strong>','Improve Training for Your Distributors, Vendors and Third Parties','','publish','closed','closed','','improve-training-for-your-distributors-vendors-and-third-parties','','','2017-07-10 15:26:53','2017-07-10 19:26:53','',0,'http://opusinside.hotsauceatl.com/?p=15',0,'post','',0),(18,3,'2017-05-02 12:00:35','2017-05-02 16:00:35','The New York State Department of Financial Services recently issued a report on Cyber Security: “<a href=\"http://www.dfs.ny.gov/reportpub/dfs_rpt_tpvendor_042015.pdf\">Update on Cyber Security in the Banking Sector: Third Party Service Providers</a>“.\r\n\r\n<strong>Key findings</strong> of this report  have been published in an article from Bank Info Security:”<a href=\"http://www.bankinfosecurity.com/banks-vendor-monitoring-comes-up-short-a-8103/op-1\"><em>Banks’ Vendor Monitoring Comes Up Short</em></a>“:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><strong>54% </strong>of the surveyed institutions say they do not conduct pre-contract, on-site assessments of high-risk vendors.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>65% </strong>say they do not conduct periodic on-site assessments to ensure ongoing security.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>21% </strong>of the institutions surveyed say they do not require third-party vendors, regardless of whether they are high- or low-risk, to prove that they have any minimum information-security requirements</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<!--more-->Security breaches are increasingly occurring via a company’s vendors and other third parties. 32% percent of all breaches in 2014 occurred as a result of external attacks targeting a vendor or other third-party (a Top 3 attack vector), according to Forrester’s Business Technographics Global Security Survey, 2014.\r\n\r\nWithout company-wide processes and procedures to ensure that all vendors and other third parties are systematically screened to verify whether or not they will have access to a company’s networks, IT systems or data, vendors can put the revenue and reputation of your organization at risk.\r\n\r\nDespite the complexities involved, understanding these risks and preparing for them is achievable. Here are four ways to identify and mitigate potential IT risks across your disparate third parties:\r\n<ol>\r\n 	<li><strong>Know Your Third Parties</strong>: While it’s easy to outsource work to third parties, it’s not so easy to know who you’re actually doing business with and who is delivering the goods or services. Companies often default to only completing due diligence and managing a limited number of “high-risk” or high spend third parties – or assuming that only traditional “IT vendors” pose an IT risk. Review whether your policies and technology allow you to identify, assess and manage all of your third parties for IT risk (as well as other risks of course)</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>Know Their Business</strong>: It is not enough to hire third parties to help your company – you also have to know what business they are doing on your behalf. Ask yourself this question: If today you had to pull a list of which of your vendors or business partners have access to employee or customer personally identifiable information (PII), or to your IT systems, how long would it take? If you had to contact those companies for additional information, do you have accurate contact details?</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>Know Their Risk</strong>: Less than half of companies regularly conduct due diligence on their third parties. While all third parties pose some level of risk, the risk and the level of seriousness differs dependent on the role of the third party. For example, third parties that deal with payroll or taxes usually pose a higher risk of security to your company’s data than the cleaning crew that comes in at night. Managing your third parties based on the risks that they pose requires knowing the risks in the first place and then having policies and procedures to control those risks throughout the life the contract.</li>\r\n 	<li><strong>Know Their Access</strong>: Not knowing that a third party had access to system passwords is not a valid excuse when your client’s records are stolen. Understanding what each party has access to – and why – will ensure that you have control over their access and can limit or deny access to sensitive information as appropriate.</li>\r\n</ol>','Cybersecurity & Vendors: Regulator Considering More Scrutiny','','publish','closed','closed','','cybersecurity-vendors-regulator-considering-more-scrutiny','','','2017-07-10 15:26:53','2017-07-10 19:26:53','',0,'http://opusinside.hotsauceatl.com/?p=18',0,'post','',0),(19,1,'2017-07-07 07:44:27','2017-07-07 11:44:27','','post-img2','','inherit','closed','closed','','post-img2','','','2017-07-07 07:44:27','2017-07-07 11:44:27','',18,'http://opusinside.hotsauceatl.com/wp-content/uploads/post-img2.png',0,'attachment','image/png',0),(27,1,'2017-07-11 04:53:02','2017-07-11 08:53:02','Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consetetur sadipscing elitr, sed diam nonumy eirmod tempor invidunt ut labore et dolore magna aliquyam erat, sed diam voluptua. At vero eos et accusam et justo duo dolores et ea rebum. Stet clita kasd gubergren, no sea takimata sanctus est Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet. Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consetetur sadipscing elitr, sed diam nonumy eirmod tempor invidunt ut labore et dolore magna aliquyam erat